[[File:Kacie Kinzer - Pop!Tech 2009 - Camden, ME (4040274223).jpg|thumb|Kacie Kinzer explaining the design choices behind the tweenbot at PopTech 2009]] '''Kacie Kinzer''' is an American designer and interactive artist.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://poptech.org/people/kacie_kinzer|title=Kacie Kinzer|last=|first=|date=|website=PopTech|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Her best known works are a series of cardboard "''tweenbots''", which were designed to get help from people, in order to complete their mission: crossing [[Washington Square Park]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2009/04/13/nyers-turn-kind-eye-to-bumbling-bots/|title=NYERS TURN KIND EYE TO BUMBLING BOTS|date=2009-04-13|work=New York Post|access-date=2017-10-18|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rezVc74eYPAC&pg=PA23&lpg=PA23&dq=Kacie+Kinzer&source=bl&ots=3GFq4G4L64&sig=r0btf213VqxtIaCVLlLSgFNmdro&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijt9-klPrWAhUGbSYKHWvmBo84FBDoAQhCMAU#v=onepage&q=Kacie%20Kinzer&f=false|title=Talk to Me: Design and the Communication Between People and Objects|last=Antonelli|first=Paola|date=2011|publisher=The Museum of Modern Art|year=|isbn=9780870707964|location=|pages=23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qDT0BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT191&lpg=PT191&dq=Kacie+Kinzer&source=bl&ots=2RLsqW-4M5&sig=PmbdN_zLxYFw2GcTqgXtqYcPxyE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwix7v7ClPrWAhWEKyYKHZTKCq84HhDoAQg3MAQ#v=onepage&q=Kacie%20Kinzer&f=false|title=Robotics: DISCOVER THE SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY OF THE FUTURE with 20 PROJECTS|last=Ceceri|first=Kathy|date=2012-08-01|publisher=Nomad Press|isbn=9781936749799|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lVoOBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq=Kacie+Kinzer&source=bl&ots=ROCkBUIbVF&sig=grywj5gKfdkVlw45Zqr0GKbOnyo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj05qfTlvrWAhUBRyYKHQ08AF44KBDoAQhEMAg#v=onepage&q=Kacie%20Kinzer&f=false|title=Social Robotics: Third International Conference on Social Robotics, ICSR 2011, Amsterdam, The Netherlands, November 24-25, 2011. Proceedings|last=Mutlu|first=Bilge|last2=Bartneck|first2=Christoph|last3=Ham|first3=Jaap|last4=Evers|first4=Vanessa|last5=Kanda|first5=Takayuki|date=2011-11-20|publisher=Springer|year=|isbn=9783642255045|location=|pages=46–47|language=en}}</ref> The bots were collected by the [[Museum of Modern Art]] and part of an exhibit on Design and Communication during 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/39112|title=Kacie Kinzer {{!}} MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref> Kinzer spoke at [[PopTech]] in 2009.<ref name=":0" />
As of 2017, Kinzer founded and works for the design firm TKOH in New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tkoh.co/|title=TOTEM|website=tkoh.co|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref>
